				&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>Maya Grinberg</name></author><gr:likingUser>09532858723748946978</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>16156993394121014454</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>06807069427704051278</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>17959305948508351143</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>07500033631459096126</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>13742756767274179987</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>17715974396124694829</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>11537795824109231272</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>16467281045281228124</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>08694071712623151681</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>15333576034043554797</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>00501227080015666174</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>17455934364732929753</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>02179651627195070043</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>01021402044189877796</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>01153223999007196894</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>11756051652522484846</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>08944199489993446061</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>02853791912162797671</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>10631262883894870527</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>15857358881284827532</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>01255583836012293595</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>01934037423649616748</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>09192250642246232171</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>05747493489537979429</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>03134508771790775690</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>13155732926764228543</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>02327550267869874911</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>08557373683724512503</gr:likingUser><source gr:stream-id="feed/http://www.socialmediaexaminer.com/feed/"><id>tag:google.com,2005:reader/feed/http://www.socialmediaexaminer.com/feed/</id><title type="html">Social Media Examiner</title><link rel="alternate" href="http://www.socialmediaexaminer.com" type="text/html"/></source></entry><entry gr:crawl-timestamp-msec="1316912854735"><id gr:original-id="http://blog.360i.com/?p=6731">tag:google.com,2005:reader/item/e9e03c438790a219</id><category term="360i News"/><category term="digital"/><category term="disclosure"/><category term="Social Media"/><title type="html">Integrity &amp;amp; Influencer Marketing: Why the Need for Digital Disclosure is Greater Than Ever</title><published>2011-09-19T15:36:45Z</published><updated>2011-09-19T15:36:45Z</updated><link rel="alternate" href="http://blog.360i.com/360i-news/integrity-influencer-marketing" type="text/html"/><content xml:base="http://blog.360i.com/" type="html">&lt;p&gt;The rise and proliferation of social media has changed the playing field of public relations forever. For most brands today, reaching the right online influencers is just as important as reaching the right media outlets. But whereas the lines of ethical boundaries for traditional journalists are relatively clear, the online space is much more nebulous.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;360i was and remains at the forefront of transparency; in 2007 we released a set of guidelines specifically around blogger relations. Within that POV, we stated our unwavering support for the &lt;a href="http://www.ftc.gov/os/2009/10/091005revisedendorsementguides.pdf"&gt;Federal Trade Commission’s endorsement guidelines&lt;/a&gt; and our dedication to transparency in DWOM® outreach (you can read our code of ethics here). The FTC best practices and guidelines from other organizations, such as WOMMA, remain as critical as they were two years ago – but the social web demands more.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now that we are fully submersed into a generation of social, our communications guidelines should evolve to better align with this new landscape. Influencer marketing grows more powerful, and more complex, each day. Social media platforms – Facebook, Twitter, Tumblr and the like – have granted individuals the ability to create their own media channels, allowing them to earn (or sometimes be “thrust into”) positions of great influence in online spaces. We need to ensure that, like blogger outreach, we are clearly disclosing our client relationships and our 360i relationship when working with influencers in emerging social platforms.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The complex trend of “individual as influencers” has especially significant implications for businesses and organizations, like 360i, that are comprised of socially active influencers in their own right. And we firmly believe that our organization, and our employees, should be accountable for the very same standards and guidelines that we require from the influencers we work with on behalf of our clients.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After months of collaborating, 360i’s influencer marketing and legal teams together launched an updated living agreement for the hundreds of socially-active influencers who make up our agency team. These guidelines encompass our agency values as well as those stated by WOMMA and the FTC.  We are committed to adhering to complete disclosure across ALL of the social platforms within which we interact as individuals.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This notion of social transparency means providing full disclosure of client relationships no matter what the forum. So whether we are individually tweeting about a colleague’s successful campaign or adding a link to a client’s story on our Facebook page, we vow to clearly communicate our relationship through the use of hashtags or other disclaimers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We have formed our guides with both the marketer and influencer in mind. Our job is to create meaningful stories and ethically share them with those who will find value in them. This will continue to be our core objective – being fair and providing value – and we will constantly reassess our guidelines to ensure that our policy is covering emerging areas of the digital environment. We invite our industry peers to join us in this commitment to transparency, and welcome your thoughts and feedback in the comments below or on Twitter @360i.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Rebecca McCuiston, VP Influencer Marketing&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;em&gt;Nicole Hering, Social Publicist&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a style="margin:12px auto 6px auto;font-family:Helvetica,Arial,Sans-serif;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;font-size:14px;line-height:normal;font-size-adjust:none;font-stretch:normal;display:block;text-decoration:underline" title="View 360i Disclosure and Code of Ethics 2011" href="http://www.scribd.com/doc/65519852/360i-Disclosure-and-Code-of-Ethics-2011"&gt;360i Disclosure and Code of Ethics 2011&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>360i</name></author><source gr:stream-id="feed/http://blog.360i.com/feed"><id>tag:google.com,2005:reader/feed/http://blog.360i.com/feed</id><title type="html">Digital Connections - 360i Blog, Digital Marketing Agency</title><link rel="alternate" href="http://blog.360i.com" type="text/html"/></source></entry><entry gr:crawl-timestamp-msec="1316908191850"><id gr:original-id="http://mashable.com/?p=734211">tag:google.com,2005:reader/item/a56f72d6635fe181</id><category term="Uncategorized"/><category term="Digital Collaboration Series"/><category term="features"/><category term="Social Media"/><title type="html">Why Your Business May Need Internal Social Software</title><published>2011-09-20T15:25:39Z</published><updated>2011-09-20T15:25:39Z</updated><link rel="alternate" href="http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Mashable/~3/UPm0C8jWI9g/" type="text/html"/><content xml:base="http://mashable.com/" type="html">&lt;p&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.aceproject.com/"&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div style="float:right;margin-bottom:10px"&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.stumbleupon.com/submit?text=sdasdasd&amp;amp;url=http://mashable.com/2011/09/20/business-social-software/"&gt;&lt;img style="border:none;margin-right:5px" src="http://5.mshcdn.com/wp-content/themes/v7/img/share-buttons/stumbleupon.png" align="right"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a href="http://digg.com/tools/diggthis/login?url=http://mashable.com/2011/09/20/business-social-software/&amp;amp;title=Why%20Your%20Business%20May%20Need%20Internal%20Social%20Software&amp;amp;related=true&amp;amp;style=true"&gt;&lt;img style="border:none;margin-right:5px" src="http://6.mshcdn.com/wp-content/themes/v7/img/share-buttons/diggme.png" align="right"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a name="fb_share" href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=http://mashable.com/2011/09/20/business-social-software/&amp;amp;src=sp" style="text-decoration:none"&gt;&lt;img style="border:none;margin-right:5px" src="http://6.mshcdn.com/wp-content/themes/v7/img/share-buttons/fb.jpg" align="right"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a href="http://api.tweetmeme.com/share?url=http://mashable.com/2011/09/20/business-social-software/&amp;amp;service=bit.ly&amp;amp;source=mashable"&gt;&lt;img style="border:none;margin-right:5px" width="51" height="61" src="http://api.tweetmeme.com/imagebutton.gif?url=http://mashable.com/2011/09/20/business-social-software/" align="right"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="float:left;margin-bottom:10px"&gt;&lt;img src="http://8.mshcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/logo-aceproject-100x50.jpg" alt="" title="logo-aceproject-100x50" width="100" height="50"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt;The &lt;a href="http://mashable.com/tag/digital-collaboration-series"&gt;Digital Collaboration Series&lt;/a&gt; is supported by &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.aceproject.com"&gt;AceProject&lt;/a&gt;, a collaboration-oriented project management web application that empowers you to manage projects, tasks and time sheets. Create your free AceProject account &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://signup.aceproject.com"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="http://7.mshcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Bees-Image-Mashable1.jpg" alt="" title="Bees Image Mashable" width="275" height=""&gt;Just like Xerox had a &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xerox_Alto"&gt;personal computer&lt;/a&gt; with a working mouse and graphic user interface a decade or so before Apple’s Macintosh, IBM had a good 10-year jump on &lt;a href="http://mashable.com/category/facebook"&gt;Facebook&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;IBM Connections, an internal employee directory made up of websites showing pictures, contact information and interests of its 300,000-plus employees, has been active for about 15 years. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It’s easy to see how IBM could have unleashed Connections into the world in 2004 (it actually did, in 2007) and created another $100 billion business for itself, but the company doesn’t look at it that way. Business social software — a catchall term for intranet versions of Facebook, &lt;a href="http://mashable.com/tag/twitter"&gt;Twitter&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="http://mashable.com/follow/topics/linkedin"&gt;LinkedIn&lt;/a&gt; — is a robust business on its own. As businesspeople have changed the way they interact and trade information in the social media age, business social software is becoming the sort of must-have that browsers and email became circa 1995.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Does Your Business Need It?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you have just five people in your business who all work out of the same office, you probably don’t need social business software or services. But what about 50? 100? Chris Crummey, IBM’s lead social evangelist, uses &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dunbar%27s_number"&gt;Dunbar’s Number&lt;/a&gt;, which sets the average person’s theoretical limit for social connections at 150. That said, Crummey says that businesses with fewer than 150 employees can benefit from using products like BluePages. “I’ve seen customers start it in one department and had only 25 people, [and they] were still successful,” Crummey says. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Nevertheless, not every business is on board with business social software at this point. Michael Fauscette, global vice president of software business solutions for &lt;a href="http://www.idc.com/"&gt;IDC&lt;/a&gt;, estimates that business social is only a $500 million segment at this point, though it’s three times as much if we consider old school collaborative software like email as part of the category. (Providers of services in the category are maddeningly vague about how much they cost. Fauscette says the range for pricing is “free to millions of dollars.”)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Why Do You Need It?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Okay, so you’ve got the requisite number of employees. What do you need social business software for? The most common answer is to tap the “Wisdom of Crowds.” That phrase came from James Surowiecki’s &lt;a href="http://www.amazon.com/Wisdom-Crowds-James-Surowiecki/dp/0385721706"&gt;influential 2004 book&lt;/a&gt; of the same name, which posited that tapping the aggregate knowledge of an assembled group will yield greater insights than mere individuals could. At &lt;a href="http://www.wellsfargo.com/"&gt;Wells Fargo&lt;/a&gt;, Nathan Bricklin, senior vice president of social strategy for wholesale banking, found that employees were already very collaborative, but he was looking to enhance that. “We saw the value in using social tools to add ‘steroids’ to the process,” he says, “so we could extend the reach of these existing personal contacts and leverage the knowledge and experience of people in a broader network.”&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Wells Fargo uses an assortment of tools to spur social media conversions within the company, including products from &lt;a href="http://www.jivesoftware.com/"&gt;Jive Software&lt;/a&gt;, Salesforce’s &lt;a href="http://mashable.com/2010/06/22/salesforce-chatter-released/"&gt;Chatter&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="http://mashable.com/2007/11/01/newsgator-opensocial/newsgator/"&gt;NewsGator&lt;/a&gt;, Socialcast, &lt;a href="http://mashable.com/follow/topics/yammer/"&gt;Yammer&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="http://mashable.com/follow/topics/bigtent/"&gt;BigTent&lt;/a&gt;. Bricklin says the software’s done what it’s promised: It’s broken down hierarchical, organizational and geographic boundaries so that everyone’s ideas are heard, it has eliminated duplicate efforts and because people are talking all the time, it’s made meetings shorter. Talk about a win-win.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;How Do You Start?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are a few variables to consider when starting a social business program. One is whether to make it voluntary or compulsory. &lt;a href="http://www.kaiserpermanente.org/"&gt;Kaiser Permanente&lt;/a&gt;, the health care company, made participation voluntary. As a result, not everyone at the company is using it. Kaiser introduced the technology in early 2009, and today, about 27,000 of its 180,000 employees are using it. “In hindsight, I might have pushed for [making it compulsory],” says Miles Appel, executive director of the company’s internal web capabilities. Still, it’s not clear what may have been achieved. Even with the voluntary system, Kaiser Permanente’s social tools (Appel, citing company policy, declined to be specific about which ones it uses), usage still falls into the 80/20 rule: About 20% of participants do 80% of the “work.” &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Meanwhile, &lt;a href="http://www.ca.com/"&gt;CA&lt;/a&gt; offers a guide to implementation. The company gave employees access to &lt;a href="http://www.newsgator.com"&gt;NewsGator&lt;/a&gt; sites to let them get used to navigation. But a month later, the company launched the platform to all employees by putting it on their homepages. Still, not all CA employees are on board. The company’s goal is to have 75% of them using the technology.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;How Do You Get The Most Out of It?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As noted, not all employees use social business software, but that’s reality. There are a lot of people on Facebook who never update their statuses, either. Still, things aren’t that clear cut. At Wells Fargo, for instance, many employees check out what’s going on on the company’s intranet social networks even if they don’t officially participate, says Bricklin. The good news is, that the network itself can be used to offer clues on improvement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;“Start with understanding what your customers are already doing in relation to your business and product in the social web,” says Kimarie Matthews, vice president of social web for Wells Fargo. “If you follow their lead and get feedback from them along the way, you will always position yourself to deliver a useful solution.”&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In other words, since the technology is still so new for many businesses, it’s a work in progress. Most businesses are still figuring out how to use social business technology, but in a world where everyone communicates via Facebook, internal micro-blogging looks like the wave of the future. Perhaps in a few years, IBM’s strategy with BluePages will look even more prescient. &lt;/p&gt;
